actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and SVG samples.

The SVG canvas writes the closing `</svg>` tag when the canvas is **disposed** (destroyed) — this is Skia's behavior for finalizing the SVG document. In your code, `using var` defers disposal to the end of the enclosing scope, so `managedStream.ToArray()` runs *before* the canvas is disposed and the closing tag is written.

Here's a workaround — use a scoped `using` block for the canvas so it's disposed before you read the stream:

```csharp
var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, managedStream))
{
    // draw operations...
    canvas.DrawMeasurement(skiaRenderer, filename, file, CanvasSize, CanvasSize);
}
// Canvas is now disposed — closing </svg> tag has been written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

Note: you can pass the `MemoryStream` directly to `SKSvgCanvas.Create` — SkiaSharp will wrap it in an `SKManagedWStream` internally.

This is the same pattern used in our [SVG canvas test](https://github.com/mono/SkiaSharp/blob/main/tests/Tests/SkiaSharp/SKCanvasTest.cs#L428-L465). Your observation that `SKFileWStream` works is consistent — file output is typically read after everything is disposed, while `MemoryStream.ToArray()` is called inline.

Regarding the difference from 2.x: the older API used `SKXmlWriter` with a different lifecycle pattern, which may have masked this ordering requirement.
